[[File:AB unfolding.jpg|thumb|300 px|Thermal unfolding curves and unfolding transition midpoints of two monoclonal antibodies. (A) Thermal unfolding curves of two [[monoclonal antibodies]] in the presence of 25mM Na-Citrate at different pH vlaues. Insets show the pH-dependence of the first unfolding midpoint (Tm1). (B) Dependence of Tm1 and Tm2 on the pH of the buffer of all tested conditions.]]
'''nanoDSF''' is a modified [[Thermal Shift Assay|differential scanning fluorimetry]] method to determine [[Protein folding|protein stability]] employing intrinsic [[Fluorescence spectroscopy#Tryptophan fluorescence|tryptophan or tyrosin fluorescence]].<ref name="nanoDSF">{{cite journal | first1 = Florian | last1 = Käufl | first2 = Frank | last2 = Rapp | name-list-format = vanc | title = nanoDSF | url = http://www.nanotemper-technologies.com/technologies/nanodsf/  | publisher = NanoTemper Technologies GmbH}}</ref><ref name="nanoDSF2">{{cite web|url=http://www.genengnews.com/new-products/protein-stability-measurement-instrument/5410/ | title = Protein Stability Measurement Instrument | journal = Genetic Engineering & Biotechnology News | date = 15 February 2015 | volume = 35 | issue = 4 }}</ref>

[[Protein folding|Protein stability]] is typically addressed by thermal or chemical unfolding experiments.<ref name="Unfolding1">{{cite journal | vauthors = Senisterra G, Chau I, Vedadi M | title = Thermal denaturation assays in chemical biology | journal = Assay and Drug Development Technologies | volume = 10 | issue = 2 | pages = 128–36 | date = April 2012 | pmid = 22066913 | doi = 10.1089/adt.2011.0390 }}</ref> In thermal unfolding experiments, a linear temperature ramp is applied to unfold proteins, whereas chemical unfolding experiments use chemical denaturants in increasing concentrations.
The thermal stability of a protein is typically described by the '[[Melting point|melting temperature]]' or 'Tm', at which 50% of the protein population is unfolded, corresponding to the midpoint of the transition from folded to unfolded.

In contrast to conventional [[Thermal Shift Assay|DSF]] methods, nanoDSF uses tryptophan or tyrosin fluorescence to monitor protein unfolding. Both the fluorescence intensity and the fluorescence maximum strongly depends on the close surroundings of the tryptophan.<ref name="Trp">{{cite  book | last = Lakowicz | first = Joseph R. | name-list-format = vanc | title=Principles of Fluorescence Spectroscopy | edition = 3rd | publisher = Springer US | date = 2006 | isbn = 978-0-387-31278-1 }}</ref> Therefore, the ratio of the fluorescence intensities at 350&nbsp;nm and 330&nbsp;nm is suitable to detect any changes in protein structure, for example due to protein unfolding.

Its applications include antibody engineering, [[membrane protein]] research, quality control and [[Pharmaceutical formulation|formulation]] development.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nanotemper-technologies.com/get-it-all/application-notes/nanodsf/|title=Application Notes: nanoDSF Technology|| first1 = Florian | last1 = Käufl | first2 = Frank | last2 = Rapp | name-list-format = vanc | publisher = NanoTemper Technologies GmbH }}</ref>

